In reverse

ÏàúÏÑúÎÇò Î∞©Ìñ•Ïù¥ Î∞òÎåÄÏù∏ ÏÉÅÌô©ÏùÑ ÎúªÌïòÎ©∞, Î≥∏Î¨∏ÏóêÏÑúÎäî Í≥ºÍ±∞ÏôÄ ÌòÑÏû¨Ïùò ÏÑ∏ÎåÄ Ïó≠Ìï†Ïù¥ Îí§Î∞îÎÄê ÏÉÅÌô©ÏùÑ Î¨òÏÇ¨Ìï† Îïå ÏÇ¨Ïö©Îê©ÎãàÎã§.

The office vibe today felt like a puzzle I couldn't interpret. As a Gen Xer, I usually tend to be the middleman, but today, everything was in reverse. Usually, I teach the kids, but today my Gen Z intern was teaching me how to use an AI tool. It felt like I was the student, and he was the master.

During the morning break, I saw a Boomer colleague, Larry, offering advice to a Millennial coworker about her career path. She didn't take it well. I could almost hear her thinking, "Mind your own business." In her eyes, it wasn't helpful advice; it was just meddling. This disconnect regarding feedback stems from the fact that younger generations place a high value on autonomy.

At lunch, we went to a department store food court. A Gen Alpha kid was running around grabbing every free sample in sight while his Millennial mom watched with a mask of exhaustion. When I accidentally tripped over a display, I sighed, but my intern laughed and said, "Look at it this way: you got all the bad luck out of the way this morning! That's your bad luck for this year done and dusted." I appreciated his optimism.

Generally speaking, older generations perceive work as a place for silence and focus, while the Gen Zers in our office see it as a social hub. By and large, we managed to get through the day without any major explosions. As I left, I realized that navigating these gaps requires us to bridge the gap by listening more and judging less. It's a constant challenge, but maybe that's just part of being a manager in 2026.
